assumptions:
  - "OpenSSL::X509::Certificate#not_after minus Time.current in test fixtures produces an Integer (the Float-division-to-integer truncation in days_until_expiry is deterministic within a single test run modulo second-level drift)"
  - "Slice 9's :degraded enum value at integer 4 is already persisted in the schema, so this slice does not need another migration to surface it"
  - "ContentMatchChecker inherits the HTTP slow-response path because ContentMatchChecker wraps HttpChecker and the job's slow_http_response? check uses site.http? || site.content_match?"

specifications:
  - "HTTP slow-response classification lives in PerformCheckJob#slow_http_response?(site, result): true iff (site.http? or site.content_match?) and site.slow_threshold_ms.present? and result.response_time_ms > site.slow_threshold_ms"
  - "SSL cert classification lives in SslChecker — the documented asymmetry from decision 3. Thresholds: days < 8 -> :down (error_message set); 8..30 -> :degraded; > 30 -> :up"
  - "SslChecker stashes classification in metadata[:classification]; the job reads it first for :ssl sites (before the error_message or status_code checks)"
  - "Slice 10 non-goal: no :degraded emission for :tcp, :dns, or :content_match-without-slow-threshold. TCP/DNS are binary signals; content-match falls back to inherited HTTP slow-response when configured"
  - "Site.slow_threshold_ms nullable integer, validated in 100..60_000. clear_irrelevant_config nulls it for :ssl/:tcp/:dns saves"
  - "PerformCheckJob#derive_status priority order (top-to-bottom first match):
      (1) SSL + metadata[:classification] -> use it directly
      (2) error_message present -> :down
      (3) metadata[:matched] == false -> :down
      (4) status_code nil -> :up
      (5) expected_status_codes present -> in?(list) ? :up : :down
      (6) slow_http_response? -> :degraded
      (7) 200..399 -> :up, else :down"
  - "The 30-day boundary for :degraded is inclusive (days <= 30 -> :degraded); 31-day cert is :up"
  - "Slow threshold is active on content-match sites too, inherited from the wrapped HttpChecker's response_time_ms"

deviations_from_plan: none

trade_offs: >
  derive_status is now 8 body lines (including comments) with 7 branches.
  That's visibly over Metz's 5-line rule but splitting it into helpers
  obscures the priority order — the order is the spec. Kept inline with
  an explicit prose comment naming the rules. Alternative considered:
  extract each branch into a predicate (ssl_classified?, error_down?,
  match_miss_down?, non_http_up?, allowlist_verdict, slow_degraded?,
  http_range_verdict) — rejected because the caller would be eight
  single-line method calls and the logic would be spread across nine
  methods instead of one.

  SslChecker's 7-day critical threshold (Slice 3) became 8-day (Slice 10).
  The Slice 3 agent-note named this as a forward reference; the change
  is not a silent regression. SSL spec cases updated to the new thresholds.

  slow_http_response? treats a zero-value slow_threshold_ms as "not set"
  via blank? — but validation rejects values below 100, so a zero is
  impossible in practice. Extra safety for anyone bypassing validation
  via raw SQL.

interfaces:
  consumed:
    - "Site#status -> String (now includes 'degraded')"
    - "Site#slow_threshold_ms -> Integer | nil"
    - "OpenSSL::X509::Certificate#not_after -> Time"
  published:
    - "Site#slow_threshold_ms= (integer writer)"
    - "Site::SLOW_THRESHOLD_RANGE -> 100..60_000"
    - "SslChecker::CRITICAL_DAYS -> 8 (previously 7)"
    - "SslChecker::WARN_DAYS -> 30"

self_review:
  tests: >
    SslChecker spec: 4 context blocks for the new 3-state classification
    (well beyond 30 days -> :up, 8..30 days -> :degraded, boundary at
    30 days inclusive -> :degraded, <8 days -> :down). Each asserts
    metadata[:classification] plus error_message presence/absence.
    PerformCheckJob spec: 4 new contexts covering ssl with :degraded
    metadata, ssl with :up metadata, http with response_time > slow_threshold
    -> :degraded, http with response_time < slow_threshold -> :up.
    Site spec: 6 slow_threshold_ms cases covering nil, valid, below-min,
    above-max, clear_irrelevant_config for tcp/ssl flips, and preservation
    on content_match sites.
  consistency: >
    SslChecker structure preserved — the classify method stays the single
    entry point from check(), and the new classification helpers
    (classify_days, cert_metadata with classification param) follow the
    Slice 3 style. SlowHttpResponse detection in the job mirrors the
    existing allowlist-check pattern (guard clause + early return).
  metz: >
    Measured. ssl_checker.rb grew from 92 to 113 lines, 11 methods.
    classify_days 3 body lines, classify 4, cert_metadata 6 (single hash).
    perform_check_job.rb grew from 53 to 84 lines, 9 methods. derive_status
    is the largest at 10 body lines; it's the declaratively-commented
    priority-order method and splitting would hurt readability. slow_http_response?
    is 4 body lines. site.rb is now 124 lines, still over the 100-line
    limit, still deferred. No methods exceed 10 body lines.
  duplication: >
    None introduced. The slow-response check uses site.http? || site.content_match?
    in one place (slow_http_response?); that same combination also appears
    in clear_irrelevant_config (slow_threshold_ms = nil unless http? || content_match?).
    Two call sites, kept inline rather than extracting a predicate.
  mocking: >
    SSL spec stubs stay the same (fake OpenSSL::X509::Certificate constructed
    inline). Job spec uses real Site records, stubs CheckDispatcher.call.
    No mocking of types we don't own beyond what Slice 3 already established.
  error_paths: >
    The error_message branch in derive_status still catches all checker-
    level failures (SSL <8 days gets an error_message, so the SSL-specific
    metadata[:classification] branch is only the deliberate "classified
    success or warning" path). Slow-response emission has 3 guards: type
    check, threshold present, response_time non-nil.
  security: >
    No new security-relevant surface. slow_threshold_ms can't be set outside
    the 100-60000 range so DoS-via-tiny-threshold is rejected at the model
    layer. Metadata[:classification] is only read for :ssl sites — a
    malicious attempt to poison metadata from another check type has no
    effect because the job only reads it when site.ssl? is true.
  performance: >
    slow_http_response? adds 3 cheap guard clauses to derive_status — O(1).
    SslChecker's days_until_expiry is one Float division. No new hot-path
    allocations.
  api: >
    Additive. Site::SLOW_THRESHOLD_RANGE, Site#slow_threshold_ms,
    SslChecker::WARN_DAYS are new public constants/attributes. PerformCheckJob#derive_status
    is private; its body changed but the callers are all internal to the
    job. SslChecker::CRITICAL_DAYS changed from 7 to 8 — not strictly
    backward-compatible if any external code referenced it, but no such
    reference exists.
  dead_code: >
    None. SLOW_THRESHOLD_RANGE referenced in validation. CRITICAL_DAYS and
    WARN_DAYS both used in classify_days. All new spec cases exercise the
    new code paths.

